# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secure-boot-chain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This may be done by hardware or firmware in the CPU, or by a separate processor in the computer system.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] On some systems, a power-on reset (POR) does not initiate booting, and the operator must initiate booting after POR completes.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] IBM uses the term **Initial Program Load** (**IPL**) on some product lines.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Restarting a computer is also called *rebooting*, which can be "hard", e.g., after electrical power to the CPU is switched from off to on, or "soft", where the power is not cut.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] On some systems, a soft boot may optionally clear RAM to zero.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Both hard and soft booting can be initiated by hardware, such as a button press, or by a software command.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Booting is complete when the operative runtime system, typically the operating system and some applications, is attained.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The process of returning a computer from a state of sleep (suspension) does not involve booting; however, restoring it from a state of hibernation does.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Minimally, some embedded systems do not require a noticeable boot sequence to begin functioning, and when turned on, may simply run operational programs that are stored in read-only memory (ROM).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] All computing systems are state machines, and a reboot may be the only method to return to a designated zero-state from an unintended, locked state.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In addition to loading an operating system or stand-alone utility, the boot process can also load a storage dump program for diagnosing problems in an operating system.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The earliest known recorded use of "boot" as the shortened form for "bootstrap" is 1975.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] There are many different methods available to load a short initial program into a computer.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] These methods range from simple, physical input to removable media that can hold more complex programs.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Early computers in the 1940s and 1950s were one-of-a-kind engineering efforts that could take weeks to program, and program loading was one of many problems that had to be solved.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] An early computer, ENIAC, had no program stored in memory but was set up for each problem by a configuration of interconnecting cables.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Bootstrapping did not apply to ENIAC, whose hardware configuration was ready for solving problems as soon as power was applied.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The EDSAC system, the second stored-program computer to be built, used stepping switches to transfer a fixed program into memory when its start button was pressed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The program stored on this device, which David Wheeler completed in late 1948, loaded further instructions from punched tape and then executed them.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The first programmable computers for commercial sale, such as the UNIVAC I and the IBM 701 included features to make their operation simpler.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] They typically included instructions that performed a complete input or output operation.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The same hardware logic could be used to load the contents of a punch card (the most typical ones) or other input media, such as a magnetic drum or magnetic tape, that contained a bootstrap program by pressing a single button.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This booting concept was called a variety of names for IBM computers of the 1950s and early 1960s, but IBM used the term "Initial Program Load" with the IBM 7030 Stretch and later used it for their mainframe lines, starting with the System/360 in 1964.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The IBM 701 computer (1952–1956) had a "Load" button that initiated reading of the first 36-bit word into main memory from a punched card in a card reader, a magnetic tape in a tape drive, or a magnetic drum unit, depending on the position of the Load Selector switch.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The left 18-bit half-word was then executed as an instruction, which usually read additional words into memory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The loaded boot program was then executed, which, in turn, loaded a larger program from that medium into memory without further help from the human operator.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The IBM 704, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 had similar mechanisms, but with different load buttons for different devices.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The term "boot" has been used in this sense since at least 1958.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Other IBM computers of that era had similar features.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] For example, the IBM 1401 system (1959) used a card reader to load a program from a punched card.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The 80 characters stored in the punched card were read into memory locations 001 to 080, then the computer would branch to memory location 001 to read its first stored instruction.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This instruction was always the same: move the information in these first 80 memory locations to an assembly area where the information in punched cards 2, 3, 4, and so on, could be combined to form the stored program.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Once this information was moved to the assembly area, the machine would branch to an instruction in location 080 (read a card) and the next card would be read and its information processed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Another example was the IBM 650 (1953), a decimal machine, which had a group of ten 10-position switches on its operator panel that were addressable as a memory word (address 8000) and could be executed as an instruction.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Thus, setting the switches to 7004000400 and pressing the appropriate button would read the first card in the card reader into memory (op code 70), starting at address 400 and then jump to 400 to begin executing the program on that card.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] IBM's competitors also offered single-button program load.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] A noteworthy variation of this is found on the Burroughs B1700, where there is neither a boot ROM nor a hardwired IPL operation.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Instead, after the system is reset, it reads and executes microinstructions sequentially from a cassette tape drive mounted on the front panel; this sets up a boot loader in RAM, which is then executed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] However, since this makes few assumptions about the system it can equally well be used to load diagnostic (Maintenance Test Routine) tapes which display an intelligible code on the front panel even in cases of gross CPU failure.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In the IBM System/360 and its successors, including the current z/Architecture machines, the boot process is known as *Initial Program Load* (IPL).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] IBM coined this term for the 7030 (Stretch), revived it for the design of the System/360, and continues to use it in those environments today.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In the System/360 processors, an IPL is initiated by the computer operator by selecting the three hexadecimal digit device address (CUU; C=I/O Channel address, UU=Control unit and Device address) followed by pressing the *LOAD* button.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] On the high end System/360 models, most System/370 and some later systems, the functions of the switches and the LOAD button are simulated using selectable areas on the screen of a graphics console, often an IBM 2250-like device or an IBM 3270-like device.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] For example, on the System/370 Model 158, the keyboard sequence 0-7-X (zero, seven and X, in that order) results in an IPL from the device address that was keyed into the input area.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The Amdahl 470V/6 and related CPUs supported four hexadecimal digits on those CPUs that had the optional second channel unit installed, for a total of 32 channels.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Later, IBM would also support more than 16 channels.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The IPL function in the System/360 and its successors prior to IBM Z, and its compatibles, such as Amdahl's, reads 24 bytes from an operator-specified device into main storage starting at real address zero.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The second and third groups of eight bytes are treated as Channel Command Words (CCWs) to continue loading the startup program (the first CCW is always simulated by the CPU and consists of a Read IPL command, 02h, with command chaining and suppress incorrect length indication being enforced).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] When the I/O channel commands are complete, the first group of eight bytes is then loaded into the processor's Program Status Word (PSW) and the startup program begins execution at the location designated by that PSW.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] IBM introduced some evolutionary changes in the IPL process, changing some details for System/370 Extended Architecture (S/370-XA) and later, and adding a new type of IPL for z/Architecture.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Minicomputers, starting with the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-5 and PDP-8 (1965) simplified design by using the CPU to assist input and output operations.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This saved cost but made booting more complicated than pressing a single button.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Minicomputers typically had some way to *toggle in* short programs by manipulating an array of switches on the front panel.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Since the early minicomputers used magnetic-core memory, which did not lose its information when power was off, these bootstrap loaders would remain in place unless they were erased.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Erasure sometimes happened accidentally when a program bug caused a loop that overwrote all of memory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Other minicomputers with such simple form of booting include Hewlett-Packard's HP 2100 series (mid-1960s), the original Data General Nova (1969), and DEC's PDP-4 (1962) and PDP-11 (1970).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] As the I/O operations needed to cause a read operation on a minicomputer I/O device were typically different for different device controllers, different bootstrap programs were needed for different devices.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] DEC later added, in 1971, an optional diode matrix read-only memory for the PDP-11 that stored a bootstrap program of up to 32 words (64 bytes).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] It consisted of a printed circuit card, the M792, that plugged into the Unibus and held a 32 by 16 array of semiconductor diodes.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] With all 512 diodes in place, the memory contained all "one" bits; the card was programmed by cutting off each diode whose bit was to be "zero".
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] DEC also sold versions of the card, the BM792-Yx series, pre-programmed for many standard input devices by simply omitting the unneeded diodes.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Following the older approach, the earlier PDP-1 has a hardware loader, such that an operator needs only push the *load* switch to instruct the paper tape reader to load a program directly into core memory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The PDP-7, PDP-9, and PDP-15 successors to the PDP-4 have an added Read-In button to read a program in from paper tape and jump to it.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The Data General Supernova used front panel switches to cause the computer to automatically load instructions into memory from a device specified by the front panel's data switches, and then jump to loaded code.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In a minicomputer with a paper tape reader, the first program to run in the boot process, the boot loader, would read into core memory either the second-stage boot loader (often called a *Binary Loader*) that could read paper tape with checksum or the operating system from an outside storage medium.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] A related example is based on a loader for a Nicolet Instrument Corporation minicomputer of the 1970s, using the paper tape reader-punch unit on a Teletype Model 33 ASR teleprinter.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The bytes of its second-stage loader are read from paper tape in reverse order.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The length of the second stage loader is such that the final byte overwrites location 7.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] After the instruction in location 6 executes, location 7 starts the second stage loader executing.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The second stage loader then waits for the much longer tape containing the operating system to be placed in the tape reader.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The difference between the boot loader and second stage loader is the addition of checking code to trap paper tape read errors, a frequent occurrence with relatively low-cost, "part-time-duty" hardware, such as the Teletype Model 33 ASR.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The earliest microcomputers, such as the Altair 8800 (released first in 1975) and an even earlier, similar machine (based on the Intel 8008 CPU) had no bootstrapping hardware as such.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] When powered up, the CPU would see memory that would contain random data.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The front panels of these machines carried toggle switches for entering addresses and data, one switch per bit of the computer memory word and address bus.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Simple additions to the hardware permitted one memory location at a time to be loaded from those switches to store bootstrap code.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Meanwhile, the CPU was kept from attempting to execute memory content.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Once correctly loaded, the CPU was enabled to execute the bootstrapping code.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This process, similar to that used for several earlier minicomputers, was tedious and had to be error-free.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The introduction of integrated circuit read-only memory (ROM), with its many variants, including mask-programmed ROMs, programmable ROMs (PROM), erasable programmable ROMs (EPROM), and flash memory, reduced the physical size and cost of ROM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This allowed firmware boot programs to be included as part of the computer.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The Data General Nova 1200 (1970) and Nova 800 (1971) had a program load switch that, in combination with options that provided two ROM chips, loaded a program into main memory from those ROM chips and jumped to it.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Digital Equipment Corporation introduced the integrated-circuit-ROM-based BM873 (1974), M9301 (1977), M9312 (1978), REV11-A and REV11-C, MRV11-C, and MRV11-D ROM memories, all usable as bootstrap ROMs.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] An Italian telephone switching computer, called "Gruppi Speciali", patented in 1975 by Alberto Ciaramella, a researcher at CSELT, included an (external) ROM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Gruppi Speciali was, starting from 1975, a fully single-button machine booting into the operating system from a ROM memory composed of semiconductors, not ferrite cores.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Although the ROM device was not natively embedded in the computer of Gruppi Speciali, due to the design of the machine, it also allowed the single-button ROM booting in machines not designed for that (therefore, this "bootstrap device" was architecture-independent), e.g., the PDP-11.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Storing the state of the machine after the switch-off was also in place, which was another critical feature in the telephone switching contest.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some minicomputers and superminicomputers include a separate console processor that bootstraps the main processor.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The PDP-11/44 had an Intel 8085 as a console processor; the VAX-11/780, the first member of Digital's VAX line of 32-bit superminicomputers, had an LSI-11-based console processor, and the VAX-11/730 had an 8085-based console processor.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] These console processors could boot the main processor from various storage devices.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some other superminicomputers, such as the VAX-11/750, implement console functions, including the first stage of booting, in CPU microcode.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] A system built using that microprocessor will have the permanent ROM occupying these special locations so that the system always begins operating without operator assistance.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] For example, Intel x86 processors always start by running the instructions beginning at F000:FFF0, while for the MOS 6502 processor, initialization begins by reading a two-byte vector address at $FFFD (MS byte) and $FFFC (LS byte) and jumping to that location to run the bootstrap code.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Apple Computer's first computer, the Apple 1, introduced in 1976, featured PROM chips that eliminated the need for a front panel for the boot process (as was the case with the Altair 8800) in a commercial computer.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Due to the expense of read-only memory at the time, the Apple II booted its disk operating systems using a series of very small incremental steps, each passing control onward to the next phase of the gradually more complex boot process.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Because so little of the disk operating system relied on ROM, the hardware was also extremely flexible and supported a wide range of customized disk copy protection mechanisms.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some operating systems, most notably pre-1995 Macintosh systems from Apple, are so closely interwoven with their hardware that it is impossible to natively boot an operating system other than the standard one.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This is the opposite extreme of the scenario using switches mentioned above; it is highly inflexible but relatively error-proof and foolproof as long as all hardware is working normally.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] A common solution in such situations is to design a boot loader that works as a program belonging to the standard OS that hijacks the system and loads the alternative OS.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This technique was used by Apple for its A/UX Unix implementation and copied by various freeware operating systems and BeOS Personal Edition 5.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some machines, like the Atari ST microcomputer, were "instant-on", with the operating system executing from a ROM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Retrieval of the OS from secondary or tertiary store was thus eliminated as one of the characteristic operations for bootstrapping.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] To allow system customizations, accessories, and other support software to be loaded automatically, the Atari's floppy drive was read for additional components during the boot process.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] There was a timeout delay that provided time to manually insert a floppy as the system searched for the extra components.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This could be avoided by inserting a blank disk.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The IBM Personal Computer included ROM-based firmware called the BIOS; one of the functions of that firmware was to perform a power-on self test when the machine was powered up, and then to read software from a boot device and execute it.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Firmware compatible with the BIOS on the IBM Personal Computer is used in IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The UEFI was developed by Intel, originally for Itanium-based machines, and later also used as an alternative to the BIOS in x86-based machines, including Apple Macs using Intel processors.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Unix workstations originally had vendor-specific ROM-based firmware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Sun Microsystems later developed OpenBoot, later known as Open Firmware, which incorporated a Forth interpreter, with much of the firmware being written in Forth.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] It was standardized by the IEEE as IEEE standard 1275-1994; firmware that implements that standard was used in PowerPC-based Macs and some other PowerPC-based machines, as well as Sun's own SPARC-based computers.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The Advanced RISC Computing specification defined another firmware standard, which was implemented on some MIPS-based and Alpha-based machines and the SGI Visual Workstation x86-based workstations.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] When a computer is turned off, its software‍—‌including operating systems, application code, and data‍—‌remains stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] When the computer is powered on, it typically does not have an operating system or its loader in random-access memory (RAM).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The small program that starts this sequence is known as a *bootstrap loader*, *bootstrap* or *boot loader*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Often, multiple-stage boot loaders are used, during which several programs of increasing complexity load one after the other in a process of chain loading.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some earlier computer systems, upon receiving a boot signal from a human operator or a peripheral device, may load a very small number of fixed instructions into memory at a specific location, initialize at least one CPU, and then point the CPU to the instructions and start their execution.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] These instructions typically start an input operation from some peripheral device (which may be switch-selectable by the operator).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Smaller computers often use less flexible but more automatic boot loader mechanisms to ensure that the computer starts quickly and with a predetermined software configuration.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In many desktop computers, for example, the bootstrapping process begins with the CPU executing software contained in ROM (for example, the BIOS of an IBM PC) at a predefined address (some CPUs, including the Intel x86 series are designed to execute this software after reset without outside help).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This software contains rudimentary functionality to search for devices eligible to participate in booting, and load a small program from a special section (most commonly the boot sector) of the most promising device, typically starting at a fixed entry point such as the start of the sector.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] On systems with those constraints, the first program loaded into RAM may not be sufficiently large to load the operating system and, instead, must load another, larger program.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The first program loaded into RAM is called a first-stage boot loader, and the program it loads is called a second-stage boot loader.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] On many embedded CPUs, the CPU built-in boot ROM, sometimes called the zero-stage boot loader, can find and load first-stage boot loaders.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Examples of first-stage (hardware initialization stage) boot loaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot and Das U-Boot.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] On the IBM PC, the boot loader in the Master Boot Record (MBR) and the Partition Boot Record (PBR) was coded to require at least 32 KB (later expanded to 64 KB) of system memory and only use instructions supported by the original 8088/8086 processors.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, UEFI or Open Firmware, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Many boot loaders (like GNU GRUB, rEFInd, Windows's BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and Windows NT/2000/XP's NTLDR) can be configured to give the user multiple booting choices.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some boot loaders can also load other boot loaders; for example, GRUB loads BOOTMGR instead of loading Windows directly.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Usually, a default choice is preselected with a time delay during which a user can press a key to change the choice; after this delay, the default choice is automatically run so normal booting can occur without interaction.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The boot process can be considered complete when the computer is ready to interact with the user, or the operating system is capable of running system programs or application programs.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some boot loaders, such as Das U-Boot and iBoot, include both first- and second-stage boot functions.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Many embedded systems must boot immediately.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] For example, waiting a minute for a digital television or a GPS navigation device to start is generally unacceptable.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Therefore, such devices have software systems in ROM or flash memory so the device can begin functioning immediately; little or no loading is necessary, because the loading can be precomputed and stored on the ROM when the device is made.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Large and complex systems may have boot procedures that proceed in multiple phases until finally the operating system and other programs are loaded and ready to execute.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Because operating systems are designed as if they never start or stop, a boot loader might load the operating system, configure itself as a mere process within that system, and then irrevocably transfer control to the operating system.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The boot loader then terminates normally as any other process would.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Most computers are also capable of booting over a computer network.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In this scenario, the operating system is stored on the disk of a server, and certain parts of it are transferred to the client using a simple protocol such as the Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over control of the booting process.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] As with the second-stage boot loader, network booting begins by using generic network access methods provided by the network interface's boot ROM, which typically contains a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) image.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] No drivers are required, but the system functionality is limited until the operating system kernel and drivers are transferred and started.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] As a result, once the ROM-based booting has completed it is entirely possible to network boot into an operating system that itself does not have the ability to use the network interface.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The boot device is the storage device from which the operating system is loaded.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Older, less common BIOS-bootable devices include floppy disk drives, Zip drives, and LS-120 drives.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] IBM-compatible PCs are examples that use horizontal integrated hardware and UEFI/BIOS firmware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Typically, the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS) will allow the user to configure a *boot order*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] If the boot order is set to "first, the DVD drive; second, the hard disk drive", then the firmware will try to boot from the DVD drive, and if this fails (e.g., because there is no DVD in the drive), it will try to boot from the local hard disk drive.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] For example, on a PC with Windows installed on the hard drive, the user could set the boot order to the one given above, and then insert a Linux Live CD in order to try out Linux without having to install an operating system onto the hard drive.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This is an example of dual booting, in which the user chooses which operating system to start after the computer has performed its power-on self-test (POST).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Several devices are available that enable the user to *quick-boot* into what is usually a variant of Linux for various simple tasks such as Internet access; examples are Splashtop and Latitude ON.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This memory location typically contains a jump instruction that transfers execution to the location of the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) start-up program.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This program runs a power-on self-test (POST) to check and initialize required devices such as main memory (DRAM), the PCI bus and the PCI devices (including running embedded option ROMs).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] One of the most involved steps is setting up DRAM over SPD, further complicated by the fact that, at this point, memory is very limited.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] After initializing required hardware, the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) goes through a pre-configured list of non-volatile storage devices ("boot device sequence") until it finds one that is bootable.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Once the BIOS has found a bootable device it loads the boot sector to linear address 7C00h (usually segment:offset 0000h:7C00h, but some BIOSes erroneously use 07C0h:0000h) and transfers execution to the boot code.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In the case of a hard disk, this is referred to as the Master Boot Record (MBR).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The conventional MBR code checks the MBR's partition table for a partition set as *bootable* (the one with *active* flag set).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] If an active partition is found, the MBR code loads the boot sector code from that partition, known as Volume Boot Record (VBR), and executes it.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The MBR boot code is often operating-system specific.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The boot sector code is the first-stage boot loader.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The boot loader was then able to load the first three sectors of the file into memory, which happened to contain another embedded boot loader able to load the remainder of the file into memory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] When Microsoft added LBA and FAT32 support, they even switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors and using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file system, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The VBR is often OS-specific; however, its main function is to load and execute the operating system boot loader file (such as `bootmgr` or `ntldr`), which is the second-stage boot loader, from an active partition.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Then the boot loader loads the OS kernel from the storage device.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] If there is no active partition, or the active partition's boot sector is invalid, the MBR may load a secondary boot loader which will select a partition (often via user input) and load its boot sector, which usually loads the corresponding operating system kernel.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In some cases, the MBR may also attempt to load secondary boot loaders before trying to boot the active partition.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] If all else fails, it should issue an INT 18h BIOS interrupt call (followed by an INT 19h just in case INT 18h would return) in order to give back control to the BIOS, which would then attempt to boot off other devices, attempt a remote boot via network.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Many modern systems (Intel Macs and newer PCs) use UEFI.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Unlike BIOS, UEFI (not **Legacy boot** via CSM) does not rely on boot sectors, UEFI system loads the boot loader (**EFI application** file in USB disk or in the EFI System Partition) directly, and the OS kernel is loaded by the boot loader.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] It is difficult to hardwire all the required logic for handling such devices, so an integrated boot ROM is used instead in such scenarios.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Also, a boot ROM may be able to load a boot loader or diagnostic program via serial interfaces like UART, SPI, USB and so on.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This feature is often used for system recovery purposes, or it could also be used for initial non-volatile memory programming when there is no software available in the non-volatile memory yet.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Many modern microcontrollers (e.g., flash memory controller on USB flash drives) have firmware ROM integrated directly into their silicon.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some embedded system designs may also include an intermediary boot sequence step.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] For example, Das U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] DRAM initialization using CPU cache as RAM) and load the larger, fully featured version of U-Boot.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Such embedded systems may used highly customized and vertical integrated hardware and software, and their boot programs may be simpler.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some CPUs and SoCs may not use CPU cache as RAM on boot process, they use an integrated boot processor to do some hardware configuration to reduce cost.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] It is also possible to take control of a system by using a hardware debug interface such as JTAG.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Such an interface may be used to write the boot loader program into bootable non-volatile memory (e.g. flash) by instructing the processor core to perform the necessary actions to program non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Alternatively, the debug interface may be used to upload some diagnostic or boot code into RAM, and then to start the processor core and instruct it to execute the uploaded code.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] This allows, for example, the recovery of embedded systems where no software remains on any supported boot device, and where the processor does not have any integrated boot ROM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] JTAG is a standard and popular interface; many CPUs, microcontrollers and other devices are manufactured with JTAG interfaces (as of 2009).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some microcontrollers provide special hardware interfaces that cannot be used to take arbitrary control of a system or directly run code, but instead allow the insertion of boot code into bootable non-volatile memory (like flash memory) via simple protocols.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Then, at the manufacturing phase, such interfaces are used to inject boot code (and possibly other code) into non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] After system reset, the microcontroller begins to execute code programmed into its non-volatile memory, just like usual processors use ROMs for booting.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Most notably, this technique is used by Atmel AVR microcontrollers, and by others as well.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In many cases, such interfaces are implemented by hardwired logic.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In other cases, such interfaces could be created by software running in integrated on-chip boot ROM from GPIO pins.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Most DSPs have a serial mode boot and a parallel mode boot, such as the host port interface (HPI boot).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In the case of DSPs, there is often a second microprocessor or microcontroller present in the system design, and this is responsible for overall system behavior, interrupt handling, dealing with external events, user interface, etc., while the DSP is dedicated to signal processing tasks only.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In such systems, the DSP could be booted by another processor, which is sometimes referred as the *host processor* (giving name to a Host Port).
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Such a processor is also sometimes referred to as the *master*, since it usually boots first from its own memories and then controls overall system behavior, including booting of the DSP, and then further controls the DSP's behavior.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The DSP often lacks its own boot memories and relies on the host processor to supply the required code instead.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The most notable systems with such a design are cell phones, modems, audio and video players and so on, where a DSP and a CPU/microcontroller coexist.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Many FPGA chips load their configuration from an external configuration ROM, typically a serial EEPROM, on power-up.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Various measures have been implemented that enhance the security of the booting process.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Some of them are made mandatory, others can be disabled or enabled by the end user.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Traditionally, booting did not involve the use of cryptography.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The security can be bypassed by unlocking the boot loader, which might or might not be approved by the manufacturer.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Modern boot loaders make use of concurrency, meaning they can run multiple processor cores and threads at the same time, which adds extra layers of complexity to secure booting.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Matthew Garrett argued that booting security serves a legitimate goal, but in doing so chooses defaults that are hostile to users.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] The system might exhibit its erroneous state in, for example, an explicit bootloop or a blue screen of death, before recovery is indicated.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Detection of an erroneous state may require a distributed event store and stream-processing platform for real-time operation of a distributed system.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] An erroneous state can trigger bootloops; this state can be caused by misconfiguration from previously known-good operations.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Recovery attempts from that erroneous state then enter a reboot, in an attempt to return to a known-good state.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] In Windows OS operations, for example, the recovery procedure was to reboot three times, the reboots needed to return to a usable menu.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] Recovery might be specified via Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), which can also implement Single sign-on (SSO) for some applications; in the zero trust security model, identification, authorization, and authentication are separable concerns in an SSO session.
[src:secure-boot-chain/booting] When recovery of a site is indicated (viz., a blue screen of death is displayed on an airport terminal screen) personal site visits might be required to remediate the situation.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] In computer security, a **chain of trust** is established by validating each component of hardware and software from the end entity up to the root certificate.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] It is intended to ensure that only trusted software and hardware can be used while still retaining flexibility.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] A chain of trust is designed to allow multiple users to create and use the software on the system, which would be more difficult if all the keys were stored directly in hardware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] It starts with hardware that will only boot from software that is digitally signed (bootloader).
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] The signing authority will only sign boot programs that enforce security, such as only running programs that are themselves signed, or only allowing signed code to have access to certain features of the machine.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] This process may continue for several layers.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] This process results in a chain of trust.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] The final software can be trusted to have certain properties because if it had been illegally modified its signature would be invalid, and the previous software would not have executed it.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] The previous software can be trusted, because it, in turn, would not have been loaded if its signature had been invalid.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] The trustworthiness of each layer is guaranteed by the one before, back to the trust anchor.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] It would be possible to have the hardware check the suitability (signature) for every single piece of software.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] However, this would not produce the flexibility that a "chain" provides.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] In a chain, any given link can be replaced with a different version to provide different properties, without having to go all the way back to the trust anchor.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] This use of multiple layers is an application of a general technique to improve scalability and is analogous to the use of multiple certificates in a certificate chain.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] In computer security, digital certificates are verified using a chain of trust.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] The trust anchor for the digital certificate is the root certificate authority (CA).
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] The certificate hierarchy is a structure of certificates that allows individuals to verify the validity of a certificate's issuer.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] Certificates are issued and signed by certificates that reside higher in the certificate hierarchy, so the validity and trustworthiness of a given certificate is determined by the corresponding validity of the certificate that signed it.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] The chain of trust of a certificate chain is an ordered list of certificates, containing an end-user subscriber certificate and intermediate certificates (that represents the intermediate CA), that enables the receiver to verify that the sender and all intermediate certificates are trustworthy.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] This process is best described in the page *Intermediate certificate authority*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/chain-of-trust] See also X.509 certificate chains for a description of these concepts in a widely used standard for digital certificates.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:secure-boot-chain/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:secure-boot-chain/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] A **Trusted Platform Module** (**TPM**) is a secure cryptoprocessor that implements the **ISO/IEC 11889** standard.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Common uses are verifying that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software and storing disk encryption keys.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] A TPM 2.0 implementation is part of the Windows 11 system requirements.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The first TPM version that was deployed was 1.1b in 2003.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) was conceived by a computer industry consortium called Trusted Computing Group (TCG).
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It evolved into *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* which was standardized by International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in 2009 as ISO/IEC 11889:2009.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* was finalized on 3 March 2011 completing its revision.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] On April 9, 2014, the Trusted Computing Group announced a major upgrade to their specification entitled *TPM Library Specification 2.0*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The group continues work on the standard incorporating errata, algorithmic additions and new commands, with its most recent edition published as 2.0 in November 2019.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] When a new revision is released, it is divided into multiple parts by the Trusted Computing Group.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Each part consists of a document that makes up the whole of the new TPM specification.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] While TPM 2.0 addresses many of the same use cases and has similar features, the details are different.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] TPM 2.0 is not backward compatible with TPM 1.2.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The TPM 2.0 policy authorization includes the 1.2 HMAC, locality, physical presence, and PCR.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It adds authorization based on an asymmetric digital signature, indirection to another authorization secret, counters and time limits, NVRAM values, a particular command or command parameters, and physical presence.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It permits the ANDing and ORing of these authorization primitives to construct complex authorization policies.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Computer programs can use a TPM for the authentication of hardware devices, since each TPM chip has a unique and secret Endorsement Key (EK) burned in as it is produced.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Security embedded in hardware provides more protection than a software-only solution.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Its use is restricted in some countries.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The primary scope of TPM is to ensure the integrity of a platform during boot time.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In this context, "integrity" means "behaves as intended", and a "platform" is any computer device regardless of its operating system.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] This is to ensure that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software, and continues until the operating system has fully booted and applications are running.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] When TPM is used, the firmware and the operating system are responsible for ensuring integrity.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] For example, the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) can use TPM to form a root of trust: The TPM contains several Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) that allow secure storage and reporting of security-relevant metrics.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] These metrics can be used to detect changes to previous configurations and decide how to proceed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Examples of such use can be found in Linux Unified Key Setup (LUKS), BitLocker and PrivateCore vCage memory encryption.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Another example of platform integrity via TPM is in the use of Microsoft Office 365 licensing and Outlook Exchange.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Another example of TPM use for platform integrity is the Trusted Execution Technology (TXT), which creates a chain of trust.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It could remotely attest that a computer is using the specified hardware and software.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Full disk encryption utilities, such as dm-crypt, can use this technology to protect the keys used to encrypt the computer's storage devices and provide integrity authentication for a trusted boot pathway that includes firmware and the boot sector.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2006, new laptops began being sold with a built-in TPM chip.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In the future, this concept could be co-located on an existing motherboard chip in computers, or any other device where the TPM facilities could be employed, such as a cellphone.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] On a PC, either the Low Pin Count (LPC) bus or the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI) bus is used to connect to the TPM chip.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The official TCG reference implementation of the TPM 2.0 Specification has been developed by Microsoft.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It is licensed under BSD License and the source code is available on GitHub.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, Intel open-sourced its Trusted Platform Module 2.0 (TPM2) software stack with support for Linux and Microsoft Windows.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Infineon funded the development of an open source TPM middleware that complies with the Software Stack (TSS) Enhanced System API (ESAPI) specification of the TCG.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It was developed by Fraunhofer Institute for Secure Information Technology (SIT).
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] IBM's Software TPM 2.0 is an implementation of the TCG TPM 2.0 specification.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It is based on the TPM specification Parts 3 and 4 and source code donated by Microsoft.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It contains additional files to complete the implementation.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on SourceForge and GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2022, AMD announced that under certain circumstances their fTPM implementation causes performance problems.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] A fix is available in form of a BIOS-Update.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The Trusted Computing Group (TCG) has faced resistance to the deployment of this technology in some areas, where some authors see possible uses not specifically related to Trusted Computing, which may raise privacy concerns.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The concerns include the abuse of remote validation of software to decide what software is allowed to run, and possible ways to follow actions taken by the user and record them in a database in a manner that is completely undetectable to the user.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The TrueCrypt disk encryption utility, as well as its derivative VeraCrypt, do not support TPM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The original TrueCrypt developers were of the opinion that the exclusive purpose of the TPM is "to protect against attacks that require the attacker to have administrator privileges, or physical access to the computer".
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The attacker who has physical or administrative access to a computer can circumvent TPM, e.g., by installing a hardware keystroke logger, by resetting TPM, or by capturing memory contents and retrieving TPM-issued keys.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The condemning text goes so far as to claim that TPM is entirely redundant.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The VeraCrypt publisher has reproduced the original allegation with no changes other than replacing "TrueCrypt" with "VeraCrypt".
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The author is right that, after achieving either unrestricted physical access or administrative privileges, it is only a matter of time before other security measures in place are bypassed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] However, stopping an attacker in possession of administrative privileges has never been one of the goals of TPM (see § Uses for details), and TPM can stop some physical tampering.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, Richard Stallman suggested replacing the term "trusted computing" with the term "treacherous computing" due to the danger that the computer can be made to systematically disobey its owner if the cryptographical keys are kept secret from them.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In August 2023, Linus Torvalds, who was frustrated with AMD fTPM's stuttering bugs, opined, "Let's just disable the stupid fTPM `hwrnd` thing." He said the CPU-based random number generation, `rdrand`, was equally suitable, despite having its share of bugs.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2010, Christopher Tarnovsky presented an attack against TPMs at Black Hat Briefings, where he claimed to be able to extract secrets from a single TPM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] He was able to do this after 6 months of work by inserting a probe and spying on an internal bus for the Infineon SLE 66 CL PC.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In case of physical access, computers with TPM 1.2 are vulnerable to cold boot attacks as long as the system is on or can be booted without a passphrase from shutdown, sleep or hibernation, which is the default setup for Windows computers with BitLocker full disk encryption.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] A fix was proposed, which has been adopted in the specifications for TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2009, the concept of shared authorisation data in TPM 1.2 was found to be flawed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] An adversary given access to the data could spoof responses from the TPM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, as part of the Snowden revelations, it was revealed that in 2010 a US CIA team claimed at an internal conference to have carried out a differential power analysis attack against TPMs that was able to extract secrets.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Main Trusted Boot (tboot) distributions before November 2017 are affected by a dynamic root of trust for measurement (DRTM) attack CVE-2017-16837, which affects computers running on Intel's Trusted eXecution Technology (TXT) for the boot-up routine.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In October 2017, it was reported that a code library developed by Infineon, which had been in widespread use in its TPMs, contained a vulnerability, known as ROCA, which generated weak RSA key pairs that allowed private keys to be inferred from public keys.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] As a result, all systems depending upon the privacy of such weak keys are vulnerable to compromise, such as identity theft or spoofing.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Cryptosystems that store encryption keys directly in the TPM without blinding could be at particular risk to these types of attacks, as passwords and other factors would be meaningless if the attacks can extract encryption secrets.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Infineon has released firmware updates for its TPMs to manufacturers who have used them.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, a design flaw in the TPM 2.0 specification for the static root of trust for measurement (SRTM) was reported (CVE-2018-6622).
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] It allows an adversary to reset and forge platform configuration registers which are designed to securely hold measurements of software that are used for bootstrapping a computer.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Fixing it requires hardware-specific firmware patches.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] An attacker abuses power interrupts and TPM state restores to trick TPM into thinking that it is running on non-tampered components.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] In 2021, the Dolos Group showed an attack on a discrete TPM, where the TPM chip itself had some tamper resistance, but the other endpoints of its communication bus did not.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] They read a full-disk-encryption key as it was transmitted across the motherboard, and used it to decrypt the laptop's SSD.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] As of 2025, a TPM is provided by nearly all PC and notebook manufacturers in their products.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] There are also hybrid types; for example, TPM can be integrated into an Ethernet controller, thus eliminating the need for a separate motherboard component.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Field upgrade is the TCG term for updating the TPM firmware.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The update can be between TPM 1.2 and TPM 2.0, or between firmware versions.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Some vendors limit the number of transitions between 1.2 and 2.0, and some restrict rollback to previous versions.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Platform OEMs such as HP supply an upgrade tool.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Since July 28, 2016, all new Microsoft device models, lines, or series (or updating the hardware configuration of an existing model, line, or series with a major update, such as CPU, graphic cards) implement, and enable by default TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] TPM endorsement keys (EKs) are asymmetric key pairs unique to each TPM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The TPM manufacturer usually provisions endorsement key certificates in TPM non-volatile memory.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The certificates assert that the TPM is authentic.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Starting with TPM 2.0, the certificates are in X.509 DER format.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] After the TPM was manufactured, the EKs cannot be changed.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] For fTPM, the EKs are stored on CPU / chipset when it was manufactured.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] These manufacturers typically provide their certificate authority root (and sometimes intermediate) certificates on their web sites.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] To utilize a TPM, the user needs a software library that communicates with the TPM and provides a friendlier API than the raw TPM communication.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Currently, there are several such open-source TPM 2.0 libraries.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Some of them also support TPM 1.2, but mostly TPM 1.2 chips are now deprecated and modern development is focused on TPM 2.0.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Typically, a TPM library provides an API with one-to-one mappings to TPM commands.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification calls this layer the System API (SAPI).
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] This way, the user has more control over the TPM operations, but the complexity is high.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] To hide some of the complexity, most libraries also offer simpler ways to invoke complex TPM operations.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification call these two layers Enhanced System API (ESAPI) and Feature API (FAPI).
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] There is currently only one stack that follows the TCG specification.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] All the other available open-source TPM libraries use their own form of richer API.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] There is an application note about an example project for the AURIX 32-bit SoC using the tpm2-tss library.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] Requires additional libraries (dotnet) to run on Linux.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] These TPM libraries are sometimes also called TPM stacks, because they provide the interface for the developer or user to interact with the TPM.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] As seen from the table, the TPM stacks abstract the operating system and transport layer, so the user could migrate one application between platforms.
[src:secure-boot-chain/trusted-platform-module] For example, by using TPM stack API the user would interact the same way with a TPM, regardless if the physical chip is connected over SPI, I2C or LPC interface to the Host system.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI replaces the BIOS that was present in the boot ROM of all personal computers that are IBM PC compatible, although it can provide backwards compatibility with the BIOS using CSM booting.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unlike the BIOS, which was originally developed by IBM as a proprietary architecture, the UEFI specification is managed by an industry consortium.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Most production firmware implementations for both remain proprietary.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Intel developed the original *Extensible Firmware Interface* (*EFI*) specification.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The last Intel version of EFI was 1.10 released in 2005.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Subsequent versions have been developed as UEFI by the UEFI Forum.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI is independent of platform and programming language, but C is used for the reference implementation TianoCore EDKII.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The original motivation for EFI came during early development of the first Intel–HP Itanium systems in the mid-1990s.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] BIOS limitations had become too restrictive for the larger server platforms for which Itanium was targeted.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The effort to address these concerns began in 1998 and was initially called *Intel Boot Initiative*.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It was later renamed to *Extensible Firmware Interface* (EFI).
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The first open-source UEFI implementation, Tiano, was released by Intel in 2004.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Tiano has since then been superseded by EDK and EDK II and is now maintained by the TianoCore community.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In July 2008, Intel ceased its development of the EFI specification at version 1.10 and contributed it to the Unified EFI Forum, which has developed the specification as the *Unified Extensible Firmware Interface* (UEFI).
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The original EFI specification remains owned by Intel, which exclusively provides licenses for EFI-based products, but the UEFI specification is owned by the UEFI Forum.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.0 of the UEFI specification was released on 31 January 2006.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 7 January 2007.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It added network authentication and the user interface architecture ("Human Interface Infrastructure" in UEFI).
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.3.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 6 April 2011.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It added Secure Boot, as well as ARM architecture support.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2018, Arm introduced Arm ServerReady, a compliance certification program intended to ensure standard operating systems and hypervisors run on Arm-based servers.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The program requires the system firmware to comply with Server Base Boot Requirements (SBBR).
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] SBBR requires UEFI, ACPI and SMBIOS compliance.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2020, Arm announced the extension of the program to the edge and IoT market.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The new program name is Arm SystemReady.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Many Linux and BSD distributions can support both recipes.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In December 2018, Microsoft announced Project Mu, a fork of TianoCore EDK II used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The project incorporates a service-based firmware delivery model.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The latest UEFI specification, version 2.11, was published in December 2024.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI supports processor architectures that are 32-bit or higher.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, only processors with a little-endian mode are supported.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unofficial UEFI support is under development for POWERPC64 by implementing TianoCore EDK II on top of OPAL, the OpenPOWER abstraction layer, running in little-endian mode.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For MIPS, there also exists an unofficial project, based on the original EDK.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, both projects have since been abandoned as of November 2016 and September 2015 respectively.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI only allows executing UEFI applications that match the firmware's bit-width, even if the processor supports smaller or larger bit-widths.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For example, a 64-bit UEFI firmware may only execute 64-bit UEFI applications, even if the processor has a 32-bit processor mode.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some low-end computers have been shipped with 32-bit UEFI firmware running on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Once a UEFI application ends the boot services and gets granted full control over the system, it becomes possible to change the processor execution mode.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, calling runtime services requires shortly changing back to the original processor mode, as runtime services may only be called from the same processor mode as the firmware implementation.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The Linux kernel added support for booting 64-bit kernels on 32-bit UEFI firmware implementations with x86-64 CPUs since version 3.15, requiring the UEFI boot loader to support the EFI handover protocol.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EFI handover protocol allows UEFI boot loaders to defer the UEFI initialization to the kernel's EFI boot stub, so that only the kernel does the UEFI initialization.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In addition to the standard PC disk partition scheme that uses a master boot record (MBR), UEFI also works with the GUID Partition Table (GPT) partitioning scheme, which is free from many of the limitations of MBR.
