[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Computers are started up by a process which has been called booting: the computer loads its operating software by means of a very small program built into the hardware, which typically loads a program, still small, to load and start the operating system (OS).
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unlike the legacy PC BIOS, UEFI does not rely on boot sectors on the computer's data storage, defining instead a boot manager as part of the UEFI specification.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] When a computer is powered on, the boot manager checks the boot configuration and, based on its settings, then executes the specified OS boot loader or operating system kernel.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The boot configuration is defined by variables stored in the computer's persistent NVRAM storage, including variables that indicate the file system paths to OS loaders or OS kernels.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] OS boot loaders can be automatically detected by UEFI, which enables easy booting from removable devices such as USB flash drives.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This automated detection relies on standardized file paths to the OS boot loader, with the path varying depending on the computer architecture.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The format of the file path is defined as <EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>\EFI\BOOT\BOOT<MACHINE_TYPE_SHORT_NAME>.EFI; for example, the file path to the OS loader on an x86-64 system is \efi\boot\bootx64.efi, and \efi\boot\bootaa64.efi on ARM64 architecture.
[src:secure-boot-chain/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Booting UEFI systems from GPT-partitioned disks is commonly called *UEFI-GPT booting*, although the UEFI specification requires MBR partition tables to be fully supported.
